{start_of_verse: Verse 1}
[G]There’s an old man in town named O’Leary but we call him [C]Lear
[D7]He lives in a world grownup people can’t get to from [G]here
[G7]But he’s magic to children and they love this gentle [C]old man
[D7]He can’t relate to grownups but we know that God [G]understands
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 2}
[C]You can find him on a bench on the courthouse lawn everyday
[D7]Where the kids and their pets all gather and joyfully [G]play
[G7]People pass and they notice how happy each little face [C]gets
[D7]When they all gather round him for candy and treats for their [G]pets
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 3}
[C]He’s a king reining there on the courthouse square
[D7]Grown people can’t get there from [G]here
[C]He sets in the sun and his subjects all come
[D7]To pay homage to good old King [G]Lear
{end_of_verse}

{start_of_verse: Verse 4}
[C]The town folks all know that the old man is slow in his mind
[D7]But God sent us a gift more precious than we’ll ever [G]find
[G7]The sun beams upon him each morning like a halo [C]of love
[D7]And wherever he goes he’s encircled by white turtle [G]doves
{end_of_verse}

